<!DOCTYPE assessment PUBLIC "-//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Assessment MathML 2.4//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_assessment_mathml_2_4.dtd"><assessment xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/" id="_u5_skeletal_homeostasis_quiz" recommended_attempts="1" max_attempts="6"><title>Skeletal Homeostasis</title><page id="b0431ba485fd49e796b9f9993a66c2b9"><multiple_choice id="sk_sys_01" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="ad236fbc3559a4d228f20357daa1ce023">Bones store calcium for use in the rest of the body. How is the homeostasis of calcium controlled? </p></body><input shuffle="true" id="bb9c02b4ca564de08f72c3ce5430c090" labels="false"><choice value="hormones">hormones from the endocrine system</choice><choice value="equilibrium">equilibrium values</choice><choice value="friction">friction created in the articulation</choice><choice value="intake">intake of calcium through milk and other products</choice></input><part id="sk_sys_01_p1"><skillref idref="skeletal_structure_SKILL" /><response match="hormones" score="10"><feedback><p id="ab800ea7e72ee4e0da2c8254fbd7befee">Correct. Calcitonin and parathyroid hormone regulate calcium homeostasis.</p></feedback></response><response match="equilibrium" score="0"><feedback><p id="af6c9ebff0bcb4c188b04d98e68ecc3d8">Incorrect. Although the calcium levels can influence the hormones, hormones regulate calcium.</p></feedback></response><response match="friction" score="0"><feedback><p id="aca3e63cdf31d441bb7f9a9455ff2e82d">Incorrect. Bones respond to force and friction, but this doesn’t regulate the calcium levels.</p></feedback></response><response match="intake" score="0"><feedback><p id="abe43ef33272945368a7f9779e06e61f4">Incorrect. Although the calcium levels can influence the hormones, hormones regulate calcium. </p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="sk_sys_27" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="af3b1e257ad8b4ca2afc3b144bb193c5b">Which cells are osteoporosis drugs intended to inhibit?</p></body><input shuffle="false" id="edb1fa4e73d24c83a2d5cff0813eadcd" labels="false"><choice value="osteoclasts">osteoclasts</choice><choice value="osteocytes">osteocytes</choice><choice value="osteoblasts">osteoblasts </choice><choice value="macrophages">macrophages</choice></input><part id="sk_sys_27_p1"><skillref idref="skeletal_levels_extracell_SKILL" /><response match="osteoclasts" score="10"><feedback><p id="aed864f3f30b348fa8790fc974883927b">Correct. Osteoporosis drugs reduce bone loss by inhibiting osteoclasts.</p></feedback></response><response match="osteocytes" score="0"><feedback><p id="addbc647d511344d4a9f64635134cb769">Incorrect. Osteoporosis drugs inhibit osteoclasts.</p></feedback></response><response match="osteoblasts" score="0"><feedback><p id="ad11d89d5d4a947c4a683b4d9b0dcaf72">Incorrect. You may think that osteoporosis drugs promote osteoblast function, but it’s easier to inhibit osteoclast function.</p></feedback></response><response match="macrophages" score="0"><feedback><p id="add094d3eb7bd4ef0b6c239de153f4f90">Incorrect. However, osteoclasts (which are inhibited by osteoporosis drugs) and macrophages are similar cells.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="sk_sys_35" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="afb23acbb8b724db8829570498df8bc9f">Increased levels of calcitonin hormone may cause what?</p></body><input shuffle="false" id="bb92678cc05b4ef28eb46daa34272a2a" labels="false"><choice value="brittle">brittle bones </choice><choice value="bone">low calcium levels in the bone</choice><choice value="blood">low calcium levels in the blood </choice><choice value="urine">increased loss of calcium to urine</choice></input><part id="sk_sys_35_p1"><skillref idref="skeletal_levels_fractures_SKILL" /><response match="brittle" score="0"><feedback><p id="adeb6ef66db9340499ad850e9424506e5">Incorrect. Calcitonin shifts the bone balance in favor of bone deposition.</p></feedback></response><response match="bone" score="0"><feedback><p id="ad71ddbf3a8ca412c99e0873edf48c2c1">Incorrect. Calcitonin shifts the bone balance in favor of bone deposition.</p></feedback></response><response match="blood" score="10"><feedback><p id="af037814e727c453abb664c4ce0abd5cd">Correct. Calcitonin shifts the bone balance in favor of bone deposition, so calcium is reduced in the blood.</p></feedback></response><response match="urine" score="0"><feedback><p id="abe18c1e0dfd748a28893f8f447f5abcd">Incorrect. Calcitonin shifts the bone balance in favor of bone deposition.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="sk_sys_36" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="ac5380d4ab847461bb3fe2034ae5bf033">Which hormones act against one another with calcium levels?</p></body><input shuffle="false" id="bc2aa55423fa4404b8a0010c01943339" labels="false"><choice value="parathyroid">parathyroid hormone and calcitonin</choice><choice value="growth">growth hormone and calcitonin</choice><choice value="insulin">insulin and calcitonin</choice><choice value="adrenaline">adrenaline and calcitonin</choice></input><part id="sk_sys_36_p1"><skillref idref="skeletal_homeo_bone_SKILL" /><response match="parathyroid" score="10"><feedback><p id="adacf018f1de14d0b9bffda96d9210210">Correct. Parathyroid hormone and calcitonin shift the balance of calcium in the body.</p></feedback></response><response match="growth" score="0"><feedback><p id="ad4a2af2a83bf47798bc55db90d9dc885">Incorrect. Calcitonin is balanced by parathyroid hormone.</p></feedback></response><response match="insulin" score="0"><feedback><p id="ab167c6bf1eb34a0a955eca99498aa269">Incorrect. Calcitonin is balanced by parathyroid hormone.</p></feedback></response><response match="adrenaline" score="0"><feedback><p id="aa469914939b440779e53099f91bb70a4">Incorrect. Calcitonin is balanced by parathyroid hormone.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="sk_sys_37" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="aaf4dbe49b18140cabd0a0bb5c20fcc07">How does vitamin D help maintain bones?</p></body><input shuffle="false" id="c3bfec082587430b8191320635c19855" labels="false"><choice value="diet">It increases calcium absorption from the diet.</choice><choice value="bones">It is a hormone that adds calcium to bones.</choice><choice value="osteoblasts">It stimulates osteoblasts.</choice><choice value="blood">It stimulates blood flow within the bones.</choice></input><part id="sk_sys_37_p1"><skillref idref="skeletal_homeo_disorders_SKILL" /><response match="diet" score="10"><feedback><p id="aa0ab14fcbbe742b6a0ce0e125d693923">Correct. Vitamin D helps in uptake of calcium.</p></feedback></response><response match="bones" score="0"><feedback><p id="aba2bca3b92e248cba3f229d3a03d3260">Incorrect. Vitamin D is not a hormone; calcitonin adds calcium to the bones.</p></feedback></response><response match="osteoblasts" score="0"><feedback><p id="ae4d5efd151fc4518a9917074e460444b">Incorrect. Vitamin D helps with digestion.</p></feedback></response><response match="blood" score="0"><feedback><p id="ad66c90bd051b479a9e358019099f8982">Incorrect. Vitamin D helps with digestion.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q56" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="af257d282211a493da315ac7b8696498e">If parathyroid hormone is abnormally high over a long period, you would expect:</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="f84928f782874924a923316db2aecfdd" labels="false"><choice value="A">abnormally strong bones</choice><choice value="B">low plasma calcium levels</choice><choice value="C">an aversion to drinking milk</choice><choice value="D">abnormally weak bones</choice></input><part id="q56_p1"><skillref idref="skeletal_homeo_bone_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="0"><feedback><p id="af926d4a5b8a14b8891a73e51988d9f0a">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback><p id="ad4efb07d2abf40e5a274ebad3aff50e0">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="C" score="0"><feedback><p id="abf00d4e739914540b7ad7c6ea972468b">Incorrect.</p></feedback></response><response match="D" score="10"><feedback><p id="ad21136e7c844499885ddcb7453937fd9">Correct.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q16" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="abfac5816654845c6b058edf1e5a7ad77">Which of the following is not a result of rickets?</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="e4441f4b9c0245d78d55f9904172aa6e" labels="false"><choice value="A">Bowed legs in children</choice><choice value="B">Improper ossification of bone in children</choice><choice value="C">Rubbery bones in children</choice><choice value="D">Bowed legs in adults</choice></input><part id="q16_p1"><skillref idref="skeletal_homeo_disorders_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="0"><feedback><p id="ad1cccef3f5054eccb07116fcf2d94199">Incorrect. Rickets does result in bowed legs in children.</p></feedback></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback><p id="aac6b7c36b550452dbb97e6871b45e40e">Incorrect. Rickets does result in improper ossification because of a lack of calcium.</p></feedback></response><response match="C" score="0"><feedback><p id="ab335a6d548b04a2998aa8ec932df7617">Incorrect. Rickets does result in rubber bones in children because they are improperly ossified.</p></feedback></response><response match="D" score="10"><feedback><p id="adda512c4e6284b3b9029127378eff8c5">Correct. Rickets does not occur in adults.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q17" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="acb2e50408e9d47f7bc601bd64ac4aa1a">Which of the following structures allow external mechanical information to be quickly transmitted?</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="b8ea746928594a69ad01ab9f886f99ed" labels="false"><choice value="A">Lacuna</choice><choice value="B">Lamellae</choice><choice value="C">Canaliculi</choice><choice value="D">Trabeculae</choice></input><part id="q17_p1"><skillref idref="skeletal_homeo_bone_force_SKILL" /><response match="A" score="0"><feedback><p id="ab89796114fbe49cc99d422e71624352b">Incorrect. Lacuna house the osteocytes.</p></feedback></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback><p id="af19a76884c994b359ec600cd61526235">Incorrect. Lamellae add strenght to bones.</p></feedback></response><response match="C" score="10"><feedback><p id="aa73fe16599ff43cda080340eab0c8380">Correct. Canaliculi are channels that allow for information transmission.</p></feedback></response><response match="D" score="0"><feedback><p id="aeb1cffe715154e4ab4c7114365d3d300">Incorrect. Trabeculae add strength to bone.</p></feedback></response></part></multiple_choice></page></assessment>
